<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-editing" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Editing</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      This chapter explains how to edit, build, preview, and serve a book
      locally. You can use any text editor to work on a <c>bookdown</c> project,
      but the chapter also includes tips for the RStudio IDE and for
      collaborating through version-control and web-based review tools.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="build-the-book">
    <title>Build the book</title>

    <p>
      To build all Rmd files into a book, the Rmd source calls
      <c>render_book()</c> from <c>bookdown</c>. It highlights
      <c>output_format</c> as the most important argument, noting that it may be
      omitted when the default output format is already declared in the YAML of
      the first Rmd file or in <c>_output.yml</c>, as discussed in
      <xref ref="configuration"/>.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>render_book(
  input = ".", output_format = NULL, ..., clean = TRUE,
  envir = parent.frame(), clean_envir = !interactive(),
  output_dir = NULL, new_session = NA, preview = FALSE,
  config_file = "_bookdown.yml"
)</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      When multiple output formats are configured in <c>_output.yml</c>, a
      simple script can render them one after another. The chapter gives this
      shell-script example for HTML and PDF output.
    </p>

    <program language="bash">
      <input>#!/usr/bin/env Rscript

bookdown::render_book("index.Rmd", "bookdown::gitbook")
bookdown::render_book("index.Rmd", "bookdown::pdf_book")</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter also discusses <c>output_dir</c>, <c>new_session</c>, and
      <c>preview</c>, and explains that generated output can be cleaned up with
      <c>bookdown::clean_book(TRUE)</c>. Because deleting files can be risky, it
      recommends keeping the project under version control such as GIT. The
      <c>new_session</c> behavior is described in <xref ref="new-session"/>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="preview-a-chapter">
    <title>Preview a chapter</title>

    <p>
      Rendering the whole book can be slow when there is a lot of computation or
      when Pandoc conversion takes time. For quicker iteration,
      <c>preview_chapter()</c> can render only the current chapter.
    </p>

    <p>
      Previewing a single chapter is useful while revising that chapter, and the
      chapter recommends previewing HTML output in particular. The trade-off is
      that cross-references to other chapters will not work, because only the
      selected chapter is rebuilt.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="serve-the-book">
    <title>Serve the book</title>

    <p>
      Instead of repeatedly calling <c>render_book()</c> or
      <c>preview_chapter()</c>, the Rmd chapter explains how to live-preview the
      book in a browser with <c>serve_book()</c>, which serves HTML output using
      the <c>servr</c> package (<xref ref="R-servr-reference"/>).
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>serve_book(
  dir = ".", output_dir = "_book", preview = TRUE,
  in_session = TRUE, quiet = FALSE, ...
)</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The root book directory is passed through the <c>dir</c> argument, and the
      default preview URL is <url href="http://127.0.0.1:4321" visual="127.0.0.1:4321"/>.
      In an interactive session this address is opened automatically, and in the
      RStudio IDE it is typically shown in the Viewer pane.
    </p>

    <p>
      The server listens for file changes and automatically recompiles Rmd files
      or refreshes the browser when supporting assets such as CSS files change.
      If recompiling the whole book is fast enough, the chapter suggests setting
      <c>preview = FALSE</c>; otherwise only modified chapters are rebuilt via
      <c>preview_chapter()</c>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The chapter closes by comparing <c>in_session = TRUE</c> and
      <c>in_session = FALSE</c>.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          With <c>in_session = TRUE</c>, you can inspect objects created while
          previewing, which is useful for interactive exploration, but the
          output may differ from a clean rebuild.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          With <c>in_session = FALSE</c>, you do not get access to those
          objects, but the output is more likely to be reproducible because it
          comes from fresh R sessions.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      For a reliable final copy of the book, it recommends running
      <c>render_book()</c> from a fresh R session.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="rstudio-ide">
    <title>RStudio IDE</title>

    <p>
      The chapter recommends using an up-to-date RStudio IDE and saving all R
      Markdown files with UTF-8 encoding, especially when files contain
      multibyte characters, as noted in <xref ref="usage"/>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Because RStudio's default Knit action uses <c>rmarkdown::render()</c>, the
      chapter shows how to switch a book project to <c>bookdown</c> by setting
      the <c>site</c> field in <c>index.Rmd</c>.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>---
title: "A Nice Book"
site: bookdown::bookdown_site
output:
  bookdown::gitbook: default
---</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      Once <c>site: bookdown::bookdown_site</c> is set in <c>index.Rmd</c> and
      the directory is an RStudio project, RStudio can recognize it as a book
      source directory. The <q>Build Book</q> button becomes available in the
      Build pane, and the Knit button previews the current chapter.
    </p>

    <p>
      The chapter also discusses RStudio addins provided by <c>bookdown</c>,
      including <q>Preview Book</q> and <q>Input LaTeX Math</q>. The Preview Book
      addin calls <c>bookdown::serve_book()</c>; to avoid blocking the current R
      session, the chapter recommends <c>bookdown::serve_book(daemon = TRUE)</c>.
      If you are not familiar with addins, the original chapter points readers
      to <url href="http://rstudio.github.io/rstudioaddins/"
      visual="rstudio.github.io/rstudioaddins/"/>. The
      <q>Input LaTeX Math</q> addin provides a text box to help type
      <latex/> math expressions (see <xref ref="fig-mathquill-pretext"/>).
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-mathquill-pretext">
      <title>The RStudio addin to help input LaTeX math.</title>
      <image source="../assets/images/mathquill.png" width="100%">
        <description>
          <p>A screenshot of the RStudio addin used to preview LaTeX math input.</p>
        </description>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Another example in the chapter is the <c>citr</c> package
      (<xref ref="R-citr-reference"/>), which provides an addin named
      <q>Insert citations</q> for inserting citations by browsing a
      bibliography database instead of remembering keys (see
      <xref ref="fig-citr-pretext"/>).
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-citr-pretext">
      <title>The RStudio addin to help insert citations.</title>
      <image source="../assets/images/citr.png" width="100%">
        <description>
          <p>A screenshot of the citation-insertion addin shown in the editing chapter.</p>
        </description>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="collaboration">
    <title>Collaboration</title>

    <p>
      Writing a book will almost surely involve more than one person. Since the
      chapters are plain-text files, the chapter recommends collaboration
      through version control, especially GIT and GitHub.
    </p>

    <p>
      Readers can contribute content directly through GitHub pull requests when
      the book source is hosted online. They can also leave feedback through
      email, GitHub issues, or page comments. The edit button mentioned in
      <xref ref="gitbook-style"/> links each page back to its Rmd source so
      those pull-request workflows are easier to use. The Rmd source links to
      GitHub's pull-request help page at <url
      href="https://help.github.com/articles/about-pull-requests/"
      visual="help.github.com/articles/about-pull-requests/"/>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The chapter uses Disqus as its example of embedded HTML page comments and
      shows the JavaScript snippet that can be saved to <c>disqus.html</c> and
      then inserted on every page via <c>after_body</c> as in
      <xref ref="yaml-options"/> (see <xref ref="fig-disqus-pretext"/> for what
      the discussion area looks like).
    </p>

    <program language="html">
      <input>&lt;div id="disqus_thread"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;script&gt;
(function() { // DON'T EDIT BELOW THIS LINE
var d = document, s = d.createElement('script');
s.src = '//yihui.disqus.com/embed.js';
s.setAttribute('data-timestamp', +new Date());
(d.head || d.body).appendChild(s);
})();
&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;noscript&gt;Please enable JavaScript to view the
&lt;a href="https://disqus.com/?ref_noscript"&gt;
  comments powered by Disqus.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/noscript&gt;</input>
    </program>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>---
output:
  bookdown::gitbook:
    includes:
      after_body: disqus.html
---</input>
    </program>

    <figure xml:id="fig-disqus-pretext">
      <title>A book page with a discussion area.</title>
      <image source="../assets/images/disqus.png" width="100%">
        <description>
          <p>A screenshot showing a discussion area embedded at the bottom of a book page.</p>
        </description>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </section>
</chapter>
